[1m19.3.[m [36mHow do I set an option that affects only the current buffer/window?[m

Some of the Vim options can have a local or global value. A local value
applies only to a specific buffer or window. A global value applies to all
the buffers or windows.

When a Vim option is modified using the "[36;1m:set[m" command, both the global and
local values for the option are changed. You can use the "[36;1m:setlocal[m"
command to modify only the local value for the option and the "[36;1m:setglobal[m"
command to modify only the global value.

You can use the "[36;1m:setlocal[m" command to set an option that will affect only
the current file/buffer:

    [36;1m:setlocal[m textwidth=70

Note that not all options can have a local value. You can use "[36;1m:setlocal[m"
command to set an option locally to a buffer/window only if the option is
allowed to have a local value.

You can also use the following command to set an option locally:

    [36;1m:let[m &l:{option-name} = <value>

For more information, read

    [36;1m:help[m :setlocal
    [36;1m:help[m local-options


[1m19.4.[m [36mHow do I use space characters for a Vim option value?[m

